A finite deterministic recognizer (FDR) is a finite automaton that accepts or rejects a given string of symbols by passing through a sequence of states defined by the string.

A deterministic recognizer is defined by a quintuplet M = (Q, Œ£, Œ¥, q0, F), where:
1. Q = {q0,‚Ä¶, qm} is a finite set of states;
2. Œ£ = {a0,‚Ä¶, an} is a finite set of input symbols (input alphabet);
3. Œ¥(x,y) is the transition function Œ¥: Q–•Œ£‚ÜíQ;
4. q0 ‚àà Q is the initial state;
5. F ‚äÇ Q is a subset of the final states.

In a deterministic automaton, there can be only one transition from state qi to letter a.

The DKR functions as follows:
1) At the initial moment of time, being in the state q0, it examines the leftmost symbol of the input string.
2) The string is read from left to right, without returns, shifting to the right by one symbol for each step of the automaton's operation.
3) In accordance with the specified transition function, the automaton changes its internal states in the process of reading the input string.
4) Having read it to the end, the automaton ends up either in one of the final states (in which case the string will be accepted or recognized by the automaton), or in some other, non-final state (in which case the string will be rejected).

